    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure! Bernoulli's principle states that an increase in the speed of a fluid occurs simultaneously with a decrease in pressure or a decrease in the fluid's potential energy. Now, imagine a wing of a plane as an airfoil, which is shaped like a teardrop. The top surface is curved, while the bottom surface is flatter. As the plane moves forward, air flows faster over the top of the wing than underneath it. This is because the curved shape of the wing forces the air to travel a longer distance in the same amount of time, much like how a river flows faster around a bend. As a result, the pressure above the wing decreases, while the pressure below the wing remains higher, creating an upward lift force. This lift force is what allows the plane to rise off the ground. So, in essence, the shape of the airfoil and Bernoulli's principle work together to create lift, allowing planes to fly.",
